            <mixed-citation publication-type="journal">Hern&#x000e1;ndez N, Bessone F, S&#x000e1;nchez A, di Pace M, Brahm J, Zapata R, A Chirino R, et al. Profile of idiosyncratic drug induced liver injury in Latin America. An analysis of published reports. Ann Hepatol 2014; 13: 231-9. <annotation><p><italic toggle="yes">(Systematic review of literature of drug induced liver injury in Latin American countries published from 1996 to 2012 identified 176 cases, none of which, however, were linked to use of aminoglycosides).</italic></p></annotation><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">24552865</pub-id></mixed-citation>
          </ref>
          <ref id="Aminoglycosides.R14">
            <mixed-citation publication-type="journal">Chalasani N, Bonkovsky HL, Fontana R, Lee W, Stolz A, Talwalkar J, Reddy KR, et al.; United States Drug Induced Liver Injury Network. Features and outcomes of 899 patients with drug-induced liver injury: The DILIN Prospective Study. Gastroenterology 2015; 148: 1340-52.e7. <annotation><p><italic toggle="yes">(Among 899 cases of drug induced liver injury enrolled in a US prospective study between 2004 and 2013, 323 [36%] cases were due to antibiotics, but none were attributed to an aminoglycoside antibiotic).</italic></p></annotation><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">25754159</pub-id></mixed-citation>
          </ref>
          <ref id="Aminoglycosides.R15">
            <mixed-citation publication-type="journal">Connolly LE, Riddle V, Cebrik D, Armstrong ES, Miller LG. A multicenter, randomized, double-blind, phase 2 study of the efficacy and safety of plazomicin compared with levofloxacin in the treatment of complicated urinary tract infection and acute pyelonephritis. Antimicrob Agents Chemother 2018; 62 (4). <annotation><p><italic toggle="yes"> (Among 145 patients with complicated urinary tract infections or pyelonephritis treated with intravenous plazomicin [10 or 15 mg/kg] or levofloxacin [750 mg] once daily for 5 days, microbiological response rates were similar in all 3 groups, but adverse event rates were less with plazomicin and there were no instances of clinically apparent liver injury with jaundice).</italic></p></annotation><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">29378708</pub-id></mixed-citation>
          </ref>
          <ref id="Aminoglycosides.R16">
            <mixed-citation publication-type="journal">Shaeer KM, Zmarlicka MT, Chahine EB, Piccicacco N, Cho JC. Plazomicin, a next-generation aminoglycoside. Pharmacotherapy 2019; 39: 77-93. <annotation><p><italic toggle="yes"> (Review of the chemistry, pharmacology, clinical efficacy and safety of plazomicin; mentions that nephrotoxicity and ototoxicity are rare; no discussion of ALT elevations or hepatotoxicity).</italic></p></annotation><pub-id pub-id-type="pmid">30511766</pub-id></mixed-citation>
